# LinkedIn Post Creation

Inputs:
- Source: main post at `src/data/content/{slug}/index.mdx` or a selected section of that post.

Output:
- Write the LinkedIn posts to `src/data/content/{slug}/socialposts/linkedin/post.txt`, post2.txt, etc.
- If `post.txt` already exists, create `post-2.txt`, `post-3.txt`, etc. Do not overwrite existing files.

Steps:
1. Read front matter from the source post (`title`, `description`, `date`, optional `tags`). Determine the canonical URL for the post.
2. Draft 6 variants of LinkedIn copy:
   - Short variant: ~500 characters
   - Longer variant: ~1,000 characters
   - Very long: more than 2,500 but under the 3,000 character limit
   - For each of these, do a version with just a single link to the original post, and another that adds 3 additional helpful links (items linked in the main post but not more than one of the three should be links to my own blog) with the link to the original post at the end.
3. Structure each variant:
   - Hook line (1 strong sentence)
   - 1‚Äì3 succinct insights or takeaways (sentences or short bullets)
   - Call to action with the post URL (plain URL, not markdown)
   - 2-5 specific hashtags at the end - not more than 5
4. Style guidelines:
   - Professional, clear, and skimmable
   - Use plain URLs (no markdown links)
   - Break paragraphs with blank lines for readability
5. Images:
   - Select 1‚Äì3 relevant images from the post directory if available
   - Do not place images inline within the text
   - At the end of the file, add an ‚ÄúImages to attach‚Äù section listing filenames to upload in LinkedIn
6. Hashtags:
   - Prefer specific topics over generic ones (e.g., `#GenerativeAI` over `#AI`)
   - Include project-relevant tags when appropriate (e.g.,   `#Astro`, `#TailwindCSS`, `#EngineeringLeadership`)
7. Saving:
   - Ensure the destination directory exists: `socialposts/linkedin/`
   - Save using Unix line endings (LF)
8. Emojis
   - Use emojis on the title line and each major point
   - Use index-finger-pointing-right for the line with link URL

